Excellent approach 👍
This is exactly how platform engineers debug Spark + Airflow deployments: validate each layer before running the real job.

We will build a very small validation DAG that checks:

1️⃣ Spark installation
2️⃣ Hadoop classpath
3️⃣ YARN connectivity
4️⃣ HDFS connectivity
5️⃣ Ability to submit a Spark job to YARN

We will start with command-line checks, then create the DAG.


---

Step 1 — Validate environment from command line (Airflow node)

Run these commands on the Airflow server.

1️⃣ Verify Spark

/app/spark/spark3/bin/spark-submit --version

Expected:

Spark 3.4.1
Scala 2.12

You already confirmed this.


---

2️⃣ Verify Hadoop installation

ls -l /opt/hadoop

Expected:

/opt/hadoop -> /app/hadoop/hadoop-3.4.1

Good in your environment.


---

3️⃣ Verify Hadoop classpath

Run:

/opt/hadoop/bin/hadoop classpath

Expected output should contain:

/app/hadoop/hadoop/share/hadoop/common
/app/hadoop/hadoop/share/hadoop/yarn
/app/hadoop/hadoop/share/hadoop/hdfs

If this command fails → Hadoop is not usable from the Airflow node.


---

4️⃣ Verify HDFS connectivity

Run:

/opt/hadoop/bin/hdfs dfs -ls /

Expected:

Found X items
drwxr-xr-x   - hdfs ...

If this fails → Hadoop config is wrong.


---

5️⃣ Verify YARN connectivity

Run:

/opt/hadoop/bin/yarn node -list

Expected:

Total Nodes: X

If this fails → YARN config not loaded.


---

6️⃣ Verify Spark → YARN submission

Run:

SPARK_DIST_CLASSPATH=$(/opt/hadoop/bin/hadoop classpath) \
/app/spark/spark3/bin/spark-submit \
--master yarn \
--deploy-mode cluster \
--class org.apache.spark.examples.SparkPi \
/app/spark/spark3/examples/jars/spark-examples*.jar 10

Expected:

Submitted application application_XXXXX

If this works → your cluster integration is correct.


---

Step 2 — Create a validation DAG

Now we automate these checks in Airflow.

Create DAG:

spark_cluster_validation_dag.py

Validation DAG

from airflow import DAG
from airflow.operators.bash import BashOperator
from datetime import datetime

SPARK_HOME = "/app/spark/spark3"
HADOOP_HOME = "/opt/hadoop"

with DAG(
    dag_id="spark_cluster_validation",
    start_date=datetime(2026,1,1),
    schedule=None,
    catchup=False,
    tags=["spark","validation"]
) as dag:

    check_spark = BashOperator(
        task_id="check_spark_version",
        bash_command=f"{SPARK_HOME}/bin/spark-submit --version"
    )

    check_hadoop = BashOperator(
        task_id="check_hadoop_classpath",
        bash_command=f"{HADOOP_HOME}/bin/hadoop classpath"
    )

    check_hdfs = BashOperator(
        task_id="check_hdfs_access",
        bash_command=f"{HADOOP_HOME}/bin/hdfs dfs -ls /"
    )

    check_yarn = BashOperator(
        task_id="check_yarn_nodes",
        bash_command=f"{HADOOP_HOME}/bin/yarn node -list"
    )

    spark_test = BashOperator(
        task_id="spark_pi_test",
        bash_command=f"""
        export SPARK_DIST_CLASSPATH=$({HADOOP_HOME}/bin/hadoop classpath)

        {SPARK_HOME}/bin/spark-submit \
        --master yarn \
        --deploy-mode cluster \
        --class org.apache.spark.examples.SparkPi \
        {SPARK_HOME}/examples/jars/spark-examples*.jar 10
        """
    )

    check_spark >> check_hadoop >> check_hdfs >> check_yarn >> spark_test


---

What this DAG validates

Task	What it proves

spark version	Spark installed
hadoop classpath	Hadoop jars visible
hdfs access	NameNode reachable
yarn nodes	ResourceManager reachable
spark_pi_test	Spark → YARN submission works



---

Expected final result

In Airflow UI you should see:

check_spark_version      ✓
check_hadoop_classpath   ✓
check_hdfs_access        ✓
check_yarn_nodes         ✓
spark_pi_test            ✓

If spark_pi_test succeeds, your main DAG will work.


